CloudHoney — GCP-Based Honeypot & Security Event Monitoring Platform
Our project, CloudHoney, is a cloud-native cybersecurity platform built entirely on Google Cloud Platform. The core idea is simple: we deploy a decoy web application — a honeypot — inside a custom VPC Network with controlled firewall rules, making it look like a real target with login pages and admin panels, then we watch what happens when it gets hit.
Rather than relying on live internet traffic, we built a Python-based attack simulator that generates realistic patterns — port scans, brute force logins, and SQL injection payloads. What makes it fully automated is Cloud Scheduler, which fires these attack scenarios on a configurable timer without any manual intervention. The system runs itself.
Every hit on the honeypot gets logged through Cloud Logging, routed to Cloud Storage, and processed by a Cloud Functions pipeline that classifies each event and triggers alerts via Pub/Sub when thresholds are crossed. Credentials never touch the codebase — they live in Secret Manager. All classified events write to Firestore, which feeds a live dashboard hosted on Cloud Run, so during the demo you can watch a scheduled attack come in, get detected, and fire an alert in real time.
GCP services used (12): Compute Engine, VPC Network, Cloud Logging, Cloud Storage, Cloud Functions, Pub/Sub, Firestore, Secret Manager, Cloud Run, Cloud IAM, Cloud Monitoring, and Cloud Scheduler.
The project mirrors real-world SOC pipeline architecture and ties directly into our cybersecurity major — now with end-to-end automation baked in from the start.
